  doi = {10.1063/1.2566637},
  urldate = {2022-09-30},
  abstract = {The common density functionals for the exchange-correlation energy make serious self-interaction errors in the molecular dissociation limit when real or spurious noninteger electron numbers  {$\mathsl{N}$} N  are found on the dissociation products. An `` {$\mathsl{M}$} M -electron self-interaction-free'' functional for positive integer  {$\mathsl{M}$} M  is one that produces a realistic linear variation of total energy with  {$\mathsl{N}$} N  in the range of  {$\mathsl{M}$}-1{$<\mathsl{N}\leqslant\mathsl{M}$} M-1{$<$}N{$\leqslant$}M , and so can avoid these errors. This desideratum is a natural generalization to all  {$\mathsl{M}$} M  of the more familiar one of one-electron self-interaction freedom. The intent of this paper is not to advocate for any functional, but to understand what is required for a functional to be  {$\mathsl{M}$} M -electron self-interaction-free and thus correct even for highly stretched bonds. The original Perdew-Zunger self-interaction correction (SIC) and our scaled-down variant of it are exactly one- and nearly two-electron self-interaction-free, but only the former is nearly so for atoms with  {$\mathsl{M}>$}2 M{$>$}2 . Thus all these SIC's produce an exact binding energy curve for  H + 2 H2+ , and an accurate one for  He + 2 He2+ , but only the unscaled Perdew-Zunger SIC produces an accurate one for  Ne + 2 Ne2+ , where there are more than two electrons on each fragment  Ne +0.5 Ne+0.5 . We also discuss  Li H + LiH+ , which is relatively free from self-interaction errors. We suggest that the ability of the original and unscaled Perdew-Zunger SIC to be nearly  {$\mathsl{M}$} M -electron self-interaction-free for atoms of all  {$\mathsl{M}$} M  stems in part from its formal resemblance to the Hartree-Fock theory, with which it shares a sum rule on the exchange-correlation hole of an open system.}
}

